{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HsRMPcUnzuB5yVLLtgqVu8","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# TASK — Calculation note: passive reactor cavity cooling\n2\t\n3\tYou are an engineer. Produce a **calculation note** for a passive **Reactor Cavity Cooling\n4\tSystem (RCCS)** — the system that removes a high-temperature reactor's decay heat after shutdown\n5\twith **no pumps**: a hot vessel wall transfers heat across an air-filled cavity to a bank of\n6\tsteel riser ducts, and the air in those ducts warms, rises by buoyancy, and carries the heat up\n7\ta chimney by natural circulation.\n8\t\n9\tEverything you need is in **`inputs/`** — facility geometry, materials, operating conditions, and\n10\twhere each quantity is measured.\n11\t\n12\t## What we want\n13\t\n14\tFor the operating cases in `inputs/04_boundary_conditions_and_test_cases.md`, predict and report\n15\t— with your reasoning and assumptions:\n16\t\n17\t- the natural-circulation air **mass flow rate**;\n18\t- the air **temperature rise** across the riser ducts;\n19\t- the **riser duct wall temperature** and the **heated-wall (mock-vessel) temperature**;\n20\t- how the removed heat splits between **radiation and convection**;\n21\t- for the accident (decay-heat) case: the **peak temperatures**, and whether the vessel **stays\n22\t  below a safe limit** (does the temperature level off, or run away?);\n23\t- how performance changes with the **outdoor ambient conditions** (air temperature, wind).\n24\t\n25\tState your confidence in each number and which assumption is the most uncertain.\n26\t\n27\t## How to work\n28\t\n29\t- You choose the methods and tools. Build from physics and the given conditions.\n30\t- Put the calculation note and all working files (scripts, models, intermediate results) in\n31\t  **`output/`**.\n32\t\n33\t## Rules\n34\t\n35\t- Do **not** look up this facility's published test reports or any pre-made model of it. (They\n36\t  exist online, and in `refs/` and `sources/` — all off-limits.) Predict the numbers yourself.\n37\t- Cite the source of any empirical correlation you use.\n38\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6fa864fa-613d-4ef1-baa7-f2191f1aaf7b","uuid":"21b7825e-d3c5-4f3c-8ed8-5038d467da3f","timestamp":"2026-07-01T21:52:13.501Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/bench/repA_baseline/TASK.md","content":"# TASK — Calculation note: passive reactor cavity cooling\n\nYou are an engineer. Produce a **calculation note** for a passive **Reactor Cavity Cooling\nSystem (RCCS)** — the system that removes a high-temperature reactor's decay heat after shutdown\nwith **no pumps**: a hot vessel wall transfers heat across an air-filled cavity to a bank of\nsteel riser ducts, and the air in those ducts warms, rises by buoyancy, and carries the heat up\na chimney by natural circulation.\n\nEverything you need is in **`inputs/`** — facility geometry, materials, operating conditions, and\nwhere each quantity is measured.\n\n## What we want\n\nFor the operating cases in `inputs/04_boundary_conditions_and_test_cases.md`, predict and report\n— with your reasoning and assumptions:\n\n- the natural-circulation air **mass flow rate**;\n- the air **temperature rise** across the riser ducts;\n- the **riser duct wall temperature** and the **heated-wall (mock-vessel) temperature**;\n- how the removed heat splits between **radiation and convection**;\n- for the accident (decay-heat) case: the **peak temperatures**, and whether the vessel **stays\n  below a safe limit** (does the temperature level off, or run away?);\n- how performance changes with the **outdoor ambient conditions** (air temperature, wind).\n\nState your confidence in each number and which assumption is the most uncertain.\n\n## How to work\n\n- You choose the methods and tools. Build from physics and the given conditions.\n- Put the calculation note and all working files (scripts, models, intermediate results) in\n  **`output/`**.\n\n## Rules\n\n- Do **not** look up this facility's published test reports or any pre-made model of it. (They\n  exist online, and in `refs/` and `sources/` — all off-limits.) Predict the numbers yourself.\n- Cite the source of any empirical correlation you use.\n","numLines":38,"startLine":1,"totalLines":38}}}
