{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GX1VQmKL8J2phXySbmaiR6","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Materials & Physical Properties\n2\t\n3\t> Model inputs. Where the source does not tabulate a property, that is noted — supply it from a\n4\t> cited standard source and state the value used.\n5\t\n6\t## 1. Surfaces & emissivities\n7\t\n8\t| Surface | Material | Emissivity ε | Note |\n9\t|---|---|---|---|\n10\t| Heated plate (mock RPV) | SAE 1020 steel, mill-scale | **0.78–0.79** | measured |\n11\t| Ceramic-heater backing sheets | sandblasted stainless | ≈ 0.90 | measured |\n12\t| Riser ducts | ASTM A500 steel, oxidized | not reported | — |\n13\t| Cavity side/back insulation faces | board insulation surface | not reported | — |\n14\t\n15\t## 2. Solid material thermal properties\n16\t\n17\tThe source does not tabulate k, ρ, c_p for the steels. Use standard values and state them:\n18\t\n19\t| Material | Use | Typical k (W/m·K) | ρ (kg/m³) | c_p (J/kg·K) |\n20\t|---|---|---|---|---|\n21\t| SAE 1020 steel | heated plate | ~50 | 7850 | ~480 |\n22\t| ASTM A500 steel | riser ducts | ~50 | 7850 | ~480 |\n23\t| ASTM A36 steel | support plate | ~50 | 7850 | ~480 |\n24\t\n25\t## 3. Insulation thermal conductivity (temperature-dependent)\n26\t\n27\tConvert from BTU·in/hr·ft²·°F with **× 0.1442 = W/m·K**:\n28\t\n29\t| Material | k @ ~200 °C | k @ ~400 °C | k @ ~600 °C |\n30\t|---|---|---|---|\n31\t| SuperIsol® (cavity walls) | ~0.060 | ~0.080 | ~0.100 W/m·K |\n32\t| Duraboard LD® (behind heaters) | — | ~0.079 | ~0.122 |\n33\t| Enerwrap 80® (chimney) | 0.043 | 0.061 | 0.085 |\n34\t\n35\tCavity-wall insulation thickness: **6 in (0.152 m)**.\n36\t\n37\t## 4. Working fluid — air\n38\t\n39\tThe coolant is **atmospheric air** (open natural-circulation loop: outdoor air in, heated air out\n40\tthe chimney). Operating pressure ≈ **1 atm (101325 Pa)** (facility near Chicago, ~180 m\n41\televation). Use temperature-dependent properties (ρ, μ, c_p, k, Pr, β) from a cited source — e.g.\n42\tCoolProp or standard correlations. The source evaluates fluid properties at the mean gas\n43\ttemperature T_m = (T_inlet + T_outlet)/2.\n44\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6fa864fa-613d-4ef1-baa7-f2191f1aaf7b","uuid":"56bebf32-62c7-4d47-abf8-271017023f64","timestamp":"2026-07-01T21:52:17.809Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/bench/repA_baseline/inputs/02_materials_and_properties.md","content":"# Materials & Physical Properties\n\n> Model inputs. Where the source does not tabulate a property, that is noted — supply it from a\n> cited standard source and state the value used.\n\n## 1. Surfaces & emissivities\n\n| Surface | Material | Emissivity ε | Note |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Heated plate (mock RPV) | SAE 1020 steel, mill-scale | **0.78–0.79** | measured |\n| Ceramic-heater backing sheets | sandblasted stainless | ≈ 0.90 | measured |\n| Riser ducts | ASTM A500 steel, oxidized | not reported | — |\n| Cavity side/back insulation faces | board insulation surface | not reported | — |\n\n## 2. Solid material thermal properties\n\nThe source does not tabulate k, ρ, c_p for the steels. Use standard values and state them:\n\n| Material | Use | Typical k (W/m·K) | ρ (kg/m³) | c_p (J/kg·K) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| SAE 1020 steel | heated plate | ~50 | 7850 | ~480 |\n| ASTM A500 steel | riser ducts | ~50 | 7850 | ~480 |\n| ASTM A36 steel | support plate | ~50 | 7850 | ~480 |\n\n## 3. Insulation thermal conductivity (temperature-dependent)\n\nConvert from BTU·in/hr·ft²·°F with **× 0.1442 = W/m·K**:\n\n| Material | k @ ~200 °C | k @ ~400 °C | k @ ~600 °C |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| SuperIsol® (cavity walls) | ~0.060 | ~0.080 | ~0.100 W/m·K |\n| Duraboard LD® (behind heaters) | — | ~0.079 | ~0.122 |\n| Enerwrap 80® (chimney) | 0.043 | 0.061 | 0.085 |\n\nCavity-wall insulation thickness: **6 in (0.152 m)**.\n\n## 4. Working fluid — air\n\nThe coolant is **atmospheric air** (open natural-circulation loop: outdoor air in, heated air out\nthe chimney). Operating pressure ≈ **1 atm (101325 Pa)** (facility near Chicago, ~180 m\nelevation). Use temperature-dependent properties (ρ, μ, c_p, k, Pr, β) from a cited source — e.g.\nCoolProp or standard correlations. The source evaluates fluid properties at the mean gas\ntemperature T_m = (T_inlet + T_outlet)/2.\n","numLines":44,"startLine":1,"totalLines":44}}}
